Section of an adult Dibothriocephalus latus containing many proglottids. The scolex was not present in this specimen. Image courtesy of the Florida State Public Health Laboratory.
Close-up of a few of the proglottids from the specimen in Figure A, showing the rosette-shaped uterus at the center of each proglottid.
Another example of a portion of a diphyllobothriid tapeworm passed spontaneously by a human patient.
Closer view of the specimen in Figure C, showing broad proglottids with craspedote (overhanging) margins.
Carmine-stained proglottids of D. latus, showing the rosette-shaped ovaries.
Close up the section shown in Figure D, showing the genital pore (arrow) opening on the ventral surface of the proglottid.
The elongate scolex and neck region of D. latus.

Sections of diphyllobothriid gravid proglottids containing eggs (arrow) in intestinal tissue, stained with H&E. Image taken at 100x magnification. Image courtesy of the University of Washington Medical Center, Seattle, WA.
